= MSP Formation

Islam has always been an important segment of Turkish public life; yet not always an important part of Turkish *political* life. The Imperial Era lacked an organized Islamic movement rivalling the reformists; Atatürk had squashed the rural remainders in the 1930s and none of the right-wing parties that rose to oppose the Jacobin-like mindset of the Kemalists had endorsed Islamic ideals, merely used them temporarily for political benefit in their appeasement of the big industry.

Seeing their inability to acquire power through outdated methods, Islamic cults and communities resorted to form ties with the petty bourgeoisie, the small artisans and shopkeepers of Anatolia who were abandoned by the capitalist right and already had traditional tendencies. Throughout the 1960s when the economic policies of first the Kemalist junta and then the AP government aggrandizing the big montage industry and the compradors marginalized the local manufacturers and artisans, Islamist figures who had infiltrated the financial world fostered a wide web of collaborators and supporters.

As AP became firmer in its economic stances and began a purge of trade associations, Islamists finally broke ties with the capitalist right and proclaimed independence by forming the short-lived MNP, the predecessor of MSP.

While MNP's lifetime was cut short by the 12 March Memorandum, the movement has now reassambled itself under a new name, the MSP. Though one notable difference is that none of the original founders of the MNP, such as the popular engineer Necmettin Erbakan, were able to participate in its founding due to a self administrated exile in Western Europe.

